    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-06-08T05:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-06-08T05:30:00-05:00" n="79"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d79">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">790B.5/6–853: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 79<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Burma (<persName type="from"
                            >Sebald</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d79fn1">Repeated to London.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rangoon</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-06-08T17:00:00+06:30"
                            >June 8, 1953—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2298. <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 2094.<note n="2" xml:id="d79fn2"
                        >See <ref target="#d70fn4">footnote 4, Document 70</ref>.</note> Have
                    received note from Foreign Minister June 5<note n="3" xml:id="d79fn3">The texts
                        of Sao Hkun Hkio’s note of June 5 and Sebald’s reply of June 8 were enclosed
                        with despatch 841 from Rangoon, June 9. (790B.5/6–953)</note> stating
                    Government Union Burma desires “defense forces have regular source of supply of
                    arms, ammunition and other warlike stores” and formally requesting their
                    purchase on reimbursable basis and accepting four specific commitments listed
                        <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 767, November 26, 1952.<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d79fn4">Not printed. The undertakings were those required by Section
                        408(e) of the Mutual Defense Assistance Act of 1949 (63 Stat. 714), as
                        amended.</note>
                </p>
                <p>In acknowledging receipt will recommend arrangements be made between War Office
                    and Army Attaché establish procedure for formulation preliminary list. Will keep
                    British fully informed and arrange day-to-day consultation <gloss
                        target="#t_BSM1">BSM</gloss> all phases preparation preliminary list.</p>
                <p>Because of objections Government Union Burma it is impossible arrange joint
                    discussion with representative War Office and <gloss target="#t_BSM1"
                        >BSM</gloss> but believe simultaneous separate consultations with full
                    understanding both parties will accomplish purpose <gloss target="#t_Deptel1"
                        >Deptel</gloss> 1459.<note n="5" xml:id="d79fn5">See <ref target="#d70fn3"
                            >footnote 3, Document 70</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sebald</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
